\abstract{The growing pace of decreasing fossil fuel resources, combined with the nervous growing degree of urgency regarding the worldwide climate crisis, has increased the urge to find sustainable and high-efficiency forms of energy conversion technologies. This chapter lays the motivational foundation of the thesis with a survey of the present global energy situation, highlighting huge volumes of industrial and home waste heat which are not recovered and converted. It is on this foundation that the thermoelectric technology is presented as an impressive solid-state solution, which is able to directly transform the thermal gradients into valuable electrical power. The three classical thermoelectric effects are discussed in systematic discussion: Seebeck effect which characterizes the voltage generated under a temperature difference; Peltier effect, characterizing the heat exchange at a junction caused by the flow of electric current; and Thomson effect, characterizing the heat interactions at a temperature difference within one conductor that carries electric current.}

