\section{Thermoelectric effects}
Thermoelectricity is the direct conversion of energy, i.e., from heat to electricity or vice versa.
In this effect, a temperature difference in the material or device would cause the flow of
current due to the potential difference or a potential difference is used to produce a
temperature difference. The bracket of the Holy trinity of thermoelectric effects: the Seebeck effect, the Peltier effect, and the Thomson effect.

