\subsection{Historical Introduction}
Thermoelectricity, which refers to the direct transformation of thermal energy and electrical energy, has a scientific provenance stretching two centuries. This is based on an initial discovery made in 1821–1823 when Thomas Johann Seebeck experimented with a closed circuit consisting of two different metals in which the junction was held at a temperature difference and found the needle of a compass to be deflected; this, later on, was explained by a phenomenon called a thermally induced electrical potential. In 1834 Jean-Charles Peltier established that electrical current passing through a junction of unlike metals would produce heating or cooling according to the direction of the current, either way. These observations were later included in a thermodynamic framework by William Thomson, who later predicted a third, eponymous phenomenon that is today named after his name. the following is a schematic of timeline of the field of TE's Journey: \newline 
