Formalism of the modern thermoelectric performance was described in the middle of the twentieth century. Much later in 1949, Abram Fedorovich Ioffe proposed the dimensionless figure of merit, \textit{zT}, and thus created a framework where large Seebeck coefficients, large electrical conductivity and low thermal conductivity are required by high-performance thermoelectrics. \cite{NWTEHIS} Materials that meet these conditions are typically highly doped semiconductor, bismuth, antimony and lead tellurides being the most proven examples so far. Since the 1990s, due to nanostructuring strategies and the global need to find sustainable energy alternatives, thermoelectric research has been revitalised and new, chalcogenide-based material systems, which this thesis has investigated, have been of interest. 
\subsection{Seebeck effect}
The Seebeck effect is the production of an electrical potential within a 
material as a temperature gradient is established. In the steady state, 
the potential produced is related to the temperature gradient by the 
equation:$ \Delta V = -S \Delta T$ where the Seebeck coefficient is represented by the symbol $S$.This can be considered a naive introduction to the Seebeck effect. However the suceeding subsections of this chapter is where we have discussed indepth for the microscopic origins of seebeckeffect.
