\subsection{Thomson effect}
In the mid-1800s, it was recognized that in a given metal or conductor 
material, the Seebeck and Peltier effects are not distinct phenomena but 
are related to one another. This was confirmed by a scientist named Lord 
Kelvin, also known as William Thomson. As a result, the Thomson effect is 
named after him. The Thomson effect is a phenomenon of reversible heating 
or cooling that happens when an electric current is made to flow through a 
material that also has a temperature gradient. The rate of heat generation 
can be represented as:
$$\dot{Q} = -\tau \mathbf{J} \cdot \nabla T$$
where $\mathbf{J}$ is the current density and $\tau$ is the Thomson 
coefficient. Lord Kelvin related the Seebeck, Peltier, and Thomson 
coefficients in 1854 and was able to develop two important equations:
$$\tau = \frac{d\Pi}{dT} - S, \qquad \Pi = ST$$
From the second equation, the first of Kelvin's relations can be rewritten 
as:
$$\tau = T\frac{dS}{dT}$$

