\subsubsection{Introduction to Landauer Theory}

Landauer theory was first formulated to describe charge transport in disordered conductors by modeling carrier transport as a transmission process between reservoirs. In this model, transport is governed by the occupation statistics of carriers in the reservoirs, which are characterized by their chemical potentials, $\mu$, and temperatures, $T$. The carrier occupation probability obeys the Fermi-Dirac distribution,

\begin{equation}
f(E) = \frac{1}{e^{(E-\mu)/k_BT} + 1}.
\end{equation}

Transport is mediated by discrete energy channels with transmission probability $T(E)$ and number of available modes $M(E)$. The electrical current is given by the difference in carrier occupation between the reservoirs,

\begin{equation}
I = \frac{2q}{h} \int T(E)M(E)\Delta f \, dE.
\end{equation}

This equation illustrates that current flow is a consequence of the asymmetry in carrier occupation between regions with different thermodynamic conditions.

For bulk materials, transport is modeled using current density, which depends on the spatial gradient of the carrier distribution function. This gives rise to the general transport equation,

\begin{equation}
J = q \int G(E)\nabla f \, dE,
\end{equation}

where $G(E)$ is the transport distribution function that lumps transmission probability and available transport modes.

This model offers a general microscopic transport theory that does not invoke specific assumptions about scattering processes.
