\subsubsection{Charge transport due to a temperature difference}
In thermoelectrics, a temperature difference leads to a variance in the 
probability of electrons being in different energy states, increasing the 
variance in distribution around the chemical potential. Due to the variation 
in the Fermi--Dirac function $f(E)$ along the position $E$, this leads to 
a variation in the number of carriers along $E$. Thus, the current is 
determined not by the number of carriers but by the variation in occupation 
with energy $E$, weighted by the transport distribution $G(E)$.

From the Landauer perspective, the current density due to a temperature difference is given by

\begin{equation}
J_{\nabla T}
=
q \nabla T
\int
G(E)
\frac{E - \mu}{T}
\left[-\frac{\partial f}{\partial E}\right]
\, dE.
\end{equation}

The part of the expression
\[
(E - \mu)\left[-\frac{\partial f}{\partial E}\right]
\]
is the selection function for thermally assisted transport. The derivative $-\frac{\partial f}{\partial E}$ selects carriers in an energy band centered at the chemical potential $\mu$ with a width of about $\pm 1.5\,k_B T$, while the factor $(E - \mu)$ favors carriers above and below $\mu$ asymmetrically.
Carriers with $E > \mu$ contribute to the current with a sign opposite 
to that of carriers with $E < \mu$.\\
Therefore, the net current is 
determined by how asymmetric the transport function $G(E)$ is inside 
the occupation window. If the function $G(E)$ is symmetric around $\mu$, 
the two contributions will cancel each other, and there will be no net 
current in the thermoelectric effect. \\ 
In summary, thermoelectric transport 
is based on how the transport function varies with energy $E$ inside the 
window where electrons are occupied, an illustration can be seen here.fig:\ref{fig:landauer_transport}, but our discussion can be only related to an open-circut scenario.

\subsubsection{Open-circut condition, introduction to Seebeck}
The Seebeck effect is concerned with the ability of a temperature difference to drive a charge and produce a voltage. \ref{fig: seebeckopen and close circit} When we probe it under open-circuit conditions, where there is no net current flow ($J = 0$), the total current is the sum of two contributions: one due to the temperature difference and the other due to the voltage difference. The voltage difference self-compensates to nullify the thermally induced current flow.
\begin{equation}
J = J_{\nabla T} + J_{\nabla V} = -v \nabla T - \sigma \nabla V
\end{equation}

Under open-circuit conditions, $J$ is zero, and the Seebeck coefficient $S$ (also denoted by $\alpha$) is given by the ratio of voltage difference to temperature difference: $\Delta V / \Delta T$. In the gradient form, this is

\begin{equation}
S = -\, \frac{\nabla V}{\nabla T} = \frac{v}{\sigma},
\end{equation}

where $\sigma$ is the electrical conductivity and $v$ is the thermoelectric transport coefficient (in units of A\,m$^{-1}$\,K$^{-1}$).
The Seebeck coefficient is a measure of the relative sensitivity of carrier transport to temperature and voltage differences.
%A material with a high Seebeck coefficient is more sensitive to temperature differences and is therefore more suitable for efficient thermoelectric energy conversion. The magnitude of the Seebeck coefficient depends on the position of the chemical potential with respect to the electronic density of states. Hence, controlling the carrier concentration is essential for high thermoelectric performance.

