\subsubsection{Heat Transport in Thermoelectric Materials}

Heat transport in thermoelectric materials occurs through both electrons and lattice vibrations (phonons). The heat carried by a particle is related to its energy and entropy. According to thermodynamic principles, the heat carried per carrier is given by

\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial Q}{\partial c} = E - \mu \quad \text{(electrons)},
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial Q}{\partial c} = E \quad \text{(phonons)}.
\end{equation}

The heat current density is expressed as

\begin{equation}
J_Q =
\int
\frac{\partial Q}{\partial c}
G(E)
\nabla f
dE.
\end{equation}

This equation provides a general description of heat transport that applies to both electrons and phonons.Heat transport depends on the same transport distribution function that governs electrical transport. Therefore, electrical conductivity, Seebeck coefficient, and thermal conductivity are fundamentally interconnected.

