\chapter{Thermoelectric materials}

\abstract{ 
This chapter based on the physical principles developed in Chapter 1 shifts the focus off the basic thermoelectric theory onto the materials science with which this technological advance could be actually accomplished. The dimesionless figure of merit, the ratio of the product of the Seebeck coefficient, electrical conductivity and thermal conductivity, or dimensionless, is denoted as \textit{\index{zT} zT}, but the mutual interdependence of these constituent factors is examined critically. The recent and state-of-the-art thermoelectric material is reviewed, followed by an extensive discussion of the degrees of freedom that can be sought to gain performance enhancement. The employment of strategies aiming to minimize lattice thermal conductivity by phonon engineering and methods in the improvement of the power factor by band-structure engineering is reviewed in detail. The quality factor is presented as a materials-level complementary presenter. The chapter also connects the gap between material properties and device level performance by explaining thermoelectric generator architecture and efficiency considerations.}
