\section{Thermoelectric Materials}
Having established the microscopic origins of thermoelectric effects in the preceding chapter, attention is now directed towards the central question of what constitutes a good thermoelectric material. The dimensionless figure of merit $zT$ and the criteria to be a high-performance thermoelectric materialsss, with particular focus on semiconducting systems in which these parameters can be most effectively optimised.

\subsection{Dimensionless Figure of Merit \textit{\index{zT} zT}}
The efficiency of a thermoelectric material is evaluated through the dimensionless figure of merit, defined as:
\[
zT = \frac{S^2 \sigma T}{\kappa},
\]
where
$S$ is the Seebeck coefficient,
$\sigma$ is the electrical conductivity,
$T$ is the absolute temperature,
$\kappa$ is the total thermal conductivity (lattice + electronic).
