The greater the figure of merit, the greater the possibilities for the generation of electricity. However, the main challenge in the optimisation of thermoelectrics is the strong interdependence among the relevant transport parameters. The carrier concentration increases electrical conductivity, but at the same time reduces the Seebeck coefficient. Similarly, any increase in electrical conductivity would necessarily increase electronic thermal conductivity according to the Wiedemann-Franz law. These mutually exclusive requirements make the independent adjustment of individual parameters extremely challenging, which is a key bottleneck to further improvement in thermoelectric performance.
$$\frac{\kappa}{\sigma} = LT $$
$$L_0 = \frac{\pi^2}{3}\left(\frac{k_B}{e}\right)^2 = 2.445 \times 10^{-8}\ \mathrm{W\,\Omega\,K^{-2}} $$
where, the Lorentz number is valid for heavily doped Semiconductors and Metals.

Semiconductors are considered to be the best materials for thermoelectric applications. This arises from their intermediate carrier concentration range, typically between 10$^{19}$ to 10$^{21}$ cm$^{-3}$, which falls within a small,\textbf{ optimistic range} where the Seebeck coefficient is significant, and the electrical conductivity is sufficiently large. On the other hand, particularly metals have too large a carrier concentration to give good Seebeck coefficients, but an insignificantly small electrical conductivity constrains insulators.

\subsection{State-of-the-Art-Thermoelectrics} From the discussion above it is evident that higher the figure of merit higher the ability to generate power, this would lead us to the intensive study of materials with large values of the dimensionless figure of merit for a thermoelectric material(zT). 
