In thermoelectrics, state-of-the-art materials are materials systems that, currently, can achieve the highest experimentally realized thermoelectric efficiencies over specific temperature ranges. This is the general nature of such materials whose electrical transport properties are optimised and maintain low lattice thermal conductivity, thus support improved thermoelectric behaviour.

The current state of the art thermoelectric materials include BismuthTelluride (Bi$_2$Te$_3$) , Tin Selenide (SnSe) and their alloys which are most effective at closer to ambient temperature, and Lead Telluride (PbTe) and the like compounds which dominate the mid-temperature regime. Silicon-Germanium (SiGe) alloys and Half-Heusler compounds have shown a promising thermoelectric performance at high operational temperatures that can be attributed to their thermal stability as well as good charge-carrier transport properties.
