New advances have focused on multifaceted crystalline structures and designed microstructures which quench phonon conduction without significantly reducing charge carrier mobility. Skutterudites, clathrates and layered Chalcogenides have become high-profile as they possess intrinsically low lattice thermal conductivities and are also tuneable in their electronic structure. In addition, techniques such as band convergence, resonant level doping, hierarchical nanostructuring have also enabled additional improvements in thermal efficiency and currently material systems have already surpassed (\textit{zT}) of unity.

These advances are the current state of the art in the study of thermoelectric materials and they still guide the current research associated with the development and exploration of next generation thermoelectric materials.
