\textbf{The lattice degree of freedom }is also inherently related to the geometry of the atoms in the crystal lattice as well as the vibration dynamics. Lattice vibrations are produced by thermal excitation and they travel as phonon which are the main conducting vectors of lattice thermal conductivity. \newline
\textbf{The degree of freedom of charge} is what characterises the behaviour of charge carriers, namely, the electrons and holes, which bring about the electrical conduction. These carriers are transported to dictate important thermoelectric parameters, such as electrical conductivity and the Seebeck coefficient.\newline 
\textbf{The spin degree of freedom} is a result of the intrinsic angular momentum of the electrons. In spite of the fact that the thermoelectric transport is mainly controlled by the charge and lattice interactions, the phenomena that involve spin can alter the scattering of carriers and affect the electronic band structure of some materials.\newline
\textbf{The orbital degree of freedom} is obtained through spatial distribution and symmetry of the electronic orbitals which form the electronic bands of solids. Degeneracy and orbital hybridization have significant effect on the electronic band structure near the Fermi level, which impact charge -carrier transport. 

Compiling, these four degrees of freedom do not exist independently in thermoelectric systems, but are irreducibly coupled. The interaction of lattice vibrations, charge carrier movement, spin interactions and orbital structure are all related and determine the electrical and thermal transport characteristics of the material. The simultaneous tuning of these coupled degrees of freedom, to maximise the thermoelectric figure of merit.

\section{Enhancement of Figure of merit}
It is evident from the preceding discussion and from Fig.\,\ref{fig:Figure of merit vs carrier concertration} that a high $zT$ is constrained to a narrow optimal range, which demands the simultaneous optimization of the interrelated transport parameters. The interrelation between the Seebeck coefficient, electrical conductivity, and thermal conductivity is a non-trivial issue since optimizing one parameter often deteriorates the performance of the other. In the following sections, the major approaches used to optimize the dimensionless figure of merit $zT$ of thermoelectric materials will be discussed. this can be achieved either by reducing the thermal conductivity or improving the power factor; now let us see the convection and neo approaches that have been used for our aim.

\subsection{Strategies for Reducing Lattice Thermal Conductivity}
The reduction of $\kappa_l$ still remains the most sought-after approach in maximizing $zT$. This is because it is relatively less coupled to other electronic transport parameters. This has prompted a wealth of research in understanding the underlying mechanisms of $\kappa_l$. The research has covered a wide spectrum of topics ranging from its relation to group velocities to lattice modes of vibration. However, new phenomena are still being discovered in this field, ranging from ultralow glass-like conductivity to rattling modes and lone pair anharmonicity. This shows that this field is still very active. The next sections discuss the main mechanisms to reduce $\kappa_l$.

