The associated phonon relaxation that one can see in Matthiessen’s rule follows a characteristic $\omega^{-4}$ frequency dependence, expressed as:
\begin{equation}
    \tau_{PD}^{-1} = \frac{V\omega^{4}}{4\pi v^{3}}\,\Gamma
\end{equation}

\noindent where $V$ is the volume per atom, $\omega$ is the phonon frequency, and $v$ 
is the acoustic phonon group velocity. The scattering parameter $\Gamma$ captures 
contributions from both mass and size mismatch between defect and host atoms, and is 
defined as:
\begin{equation}
    \Gamma = \sum_{i} f_{i}\left(1 - \frac{m_{i}}{\bar{m}}\right)^{2} 
           + \sum_{i} f_{i}\left(1 - \frac{r_{i}}{\bar{r}}\right)^{2}
\end{equation}

\noindent where $m_{i}$ and $r_{i}$ are the mass and atomic radius of species $i$, 
$\bar{m}$ and $\bar{r}$ are the corresponding averages over all atoms, and $f_{i}$ is the fractional site occupancy of species $i$. This strong frequency dependence, these defects can mitigate the phonon with high frequencies making them worthwile to investigate.
        
