     \subsubsection{Nanostructuring and Size Effects (Reduced Dimensionality)}
Size effects are the basis of thermoelectric nanocomposites and low-dimensional thermoelectric materials \cite{science-tritt}. Classical and quantum size effects are of great importance for understanding transport properties. 

The classical size effect is mainly related to the phonon mean free path limited by scattering. As heat transport is carried out by phonons with a wide temperature-dependent spectrum of energies and momenta, it is necessary to suppress the lattice thermal conductivity ($\kappa_L$) over a wide temperature range by hierarchical microstructures scattering phonons on various scales.

In the ultimate size effect, when the phonon mean free path is close to the interatomic distance, heat transport is described in the so called amorphous limit. In this case, heat transport is carried out by diffusively hopping vibrational modes instead of propagating phonons. The minimum lattice thermal conductivity ($\kappa_{\min}$) is described by the following equation

\begin{equation}
\kappa_{\min} =
\left(\frac{\pi}{6}\right)^{1/3}
k_B n_a^{2/3}
\sum_i v_i
\left(\frac{T}{\Theta_i}\right)^2
\int_0^{\Theta_i/T}
\frac{x^3 e^x}{(e^x - 1)^2} \, dx
\label{eq:kmin}
\end{equation}

where $n_a$ is the atomic number density, $k_B$ is the Boltzmann constant, $v_i$ is the sound velocity for each phonon polarization branch, and $\Theta_i$ is the cutoff temperature corresponding to the maximum phonon frequency:

\begin{equation}
\Theta_i = \frac{\hbar v_i}{k_B} (6\pi^2 n_a)^{1/3}
\end{equation}

Here, $\hbar$ is the reduced Planck constant. Equation~(\ref{eq:kmin}) represents the lower bound of lattice thermal conductivity when phonon transport becomes completely diffusion-dominated. \cite{Lowest k cond}

