\subsubsection{Band Convergence}
Band convergence causes the presence of multiple extrema of different bands to come very close to degeneracy, thereby increasing the valley degeneracy, i.e., the valley degeneracy $N_v$, whereas the inertial effective mass of the charge carriers remains unchanged. An increased valley degeneracy results in a greater DOS effective mass, i.e., $m_d^{*}=N_v^{2/3}m_b^{*}$, thereby enhancing the Seebeck coefficient, whereas the band effective mass $m_b^{*}$ maintains the mobility of the charge carriers.

\subsubsection{Entropy Engineering}
Entropy engineering harnesses the configurational disorder of multicomponent solid solutions—often termed high-entropy alloys or highentropy ceramics to simultaneously scatter phonons and tailor the electronic structure in thermoelectric materials. By mixing five or more principal elements on a single crystallographic sublattice in near-equimolar proportions, a large configurational entropy stabilises a single-phase solid solution and introduces severe mass and strain fluctuations across the lattice. 

\vspace{-1cm}
\begin{tcolorbox}
The ideal configurational entropy per site for an $n$-component equimolar mixture on a single sublattice is:
\begin{equation}
\Delta S_{\mathrm{mix}} = -R \sum_{i=1}^{n} x_i \ln x_i = R \ln n
\end{equation}
where $R$ is the gas constant and $x_i = 1/n$ is the mole fraction of each constituent. A mixture is conventionally classified as high-entropy when $\Delta S_{\mathrm{mix}} \geq 1.5\,R$, corresponding to $n \geq 5$.
\end{tcolorbox}

\section{Quality Factor}
A detour; it is necessary to define a parameter that  unites nearly all the sub-classes of thermoelectric materials and that is indispensable, i.e the thermoelectric quality factor, $b$. 
\begin{tcolorbox}[enhanced jigsaw,breakable,pad at break*=1mm,
  colback=blue!5!white,colframe=blue!75!black,title=Quality Factor in Thermoelectric Performance]

Although the thermoelectric figure of merit, $zT$, is usually expressed in terms of three interdependent material parameters, the Seebeck coefficient $S$, electrical conductivity $\sigma$, and thermal conductivity $\kappa$
\begin{equation}
zT = \frac{S^2 \sigma T}{\kappa},
\end{equation}
a more fundamental perspective emerges when these are consolidated into a single dimensionless quantity known as the quality factor, or $b$-factor. As shown by Witkoske \textit{et al.}, \cite{witkoske}, the generalized $b$-factor is defined as
\begin{equation}
b_L(E_F) \equiv \frac{\sigma(E_F)\,T}{\kappa_L}
\left(\frac{k_B}{q}\right)^2 ,
\end{equation}
where $\sigma(E_F)$ is the electrical conductivity evaluated at the Fermi energy, $T$ is the absolute temperature, $\kappa_L$ is the lattice thermal conductivity,$q$ is charge. This expression captures the fundamental competition between electrical transport and lattice thermal transport.
Remarkably, numerical simulations across more than a dozen complex band structures including multi-valley, anisotropic, and two-dimensional syst      ems demonstrate that the peak $zT$ at a given $b$-factor is nearly identical to that of a simple parabolic band with acoustic deformation potential scattering. This apparent universality arises because any modification to the electronic structure that enhances the Seebeck coefficient simultaneously increases the Lorenz number, and vice versa, leaving $zT$ largely unchanged at fixed $b_L$.
\begin{equation}
    zT = \frac{S'^2}{L' + 1/b_L}
\end{equation}
where $S' =s/(k_B/q)$ and$ L' = L/(k_B /q)^2$ are the dimensionless Seebeck coefficient and the Lorenz number respectively.
The physical implication is significant: thermoelectric performance is not governed independently by $S$, $\sigma$, or $\kappa_e$, but rather by the ratio of electrical conductivity to lattice thermal conductivity. \newline
%Band engineering strategies that aim to enhance $S$ or the Lorenz number in isolation are therefore inherently limited unless they also increase this underlying ratio. Consequently, the most effective routes to achieving high $zT$ remain those that simultaneously maximize $\sigma$ --- through reduced electron--phonon coupling and high carrier velocity --- while minimizing $\kappa_L$ via phonon scattering mechanisms.
 The quality factor thus serves as a unifying diagnostic: a material with a large $b_L$ possesses strong intrinsic thermoelectric potential regardless of band complexity, whereas a material with a small $b_L$ cannot attain high performance through Seebeck enhancement alone.
\end{tcolorbox}
