\section{From Materials to Devices: Thermoelectric Generators}
From the discussion so far, it should be emphasised that everything covered until now concerns only the intrinsic properties of thermoelectric materials—their electronic band structures, phonon spectra, and the various strategies available to optimise $zT$. However, to address real-world energy-conversion needs, we ultimately require an actual \emph{device} capable of generating electricity from a temperature difference (or, conversely, pumping heat with an applied current). This is only possible when individual thermoelectric materials are assembled into a functional thermoelectric (TE) module.

