A thermoelectric device is an assembly of multiple \emph{thermoelectric couples}, each consisting of one \textbf{p-type} leg (hole-rich, electron-deficient) electrically connected in series with one \textbf{n-type} leg (electron-rich, hole-poor). The legs are connected thermally in parallel—both legs span the same hot-side and cold-side temperatures—but electrically in series through metallic interconnects so that the Seebeck voltages of successive couples add cumulatively. A practical module may contain tens to hundreds of such couples sandwiched between two electrically insulating but thermally conducting ceramic plates.\\

Figure~\ref{fig:TE_module_schematic} illustrates the layered architecture of a single thermoelectric couple within a module. Starting from the hot side (top) and moving toward the 
