\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Ceramic substrate (hot/cold side):} A thin parchment of alumina (Al$_2$O$_3$) that electrically insulates the internal components from the external heat source while providing efficient thermal conduction into the module.
    \item \textbf{Copper interconnect (hot/cold side):} A metallic bridge, typically copper to form a ohmic contact and electrically connects the top of the p-type leg to the top of the n-type leg., 
    \item \textbf{Thermoelectric legs:} The p-type and n-type semiconductor elements that generate a voltage via the Seebeck effect when subjected to a temperature gradient.
    \item \textbf{Heat sink:} A finned metallic structure (typically aluminium or copper) that rejects waste heat to the ambient environment, maintaining the cold-side temperature as low as practicable.
\end{enumerate}


\subsection{Device Efficiency and Current Status}

The conversion efficiency $\eta$ of a thermoelectric generator operating between a hot-side temperature $T_H$ and a cold-side temperature $T_C$ is bounded by the Carnot limit $\eta_C = 1 - T_C/T_H$ and depends on the device-level figure of merit $zT_{\mathrm{avg}}$ averaged over the working temperature range:

\begin{tcolorbox}
The maximum thermoelectric conversion efficiency of a single-stage generator is given by:
\begin{equation}
    \eta_{\max} = \frac{T_H - T_C}{T_H}\;\cdot\;\frac{\sqrt{1 + zT_{\mathrm{avg}}} - 1}{\sqrt{1 + zT_{\mathrm{avg}}} + T_C/T_H}
\end{equation}
where $zT_{\mathrm{avg}}$ is the figure of merit averaged over the temperature interval $[T_C,\,T_H]$, and the first factor is the Carnot efficiency.
\end{tcolorbox}
