\section{Classification of Thermoelectric Materials}
Thermoelectric materials are typically organised into subclasses on the basis of
two complementary criteria:

\emph{chemical composition} (the constituent elements
and their bonding character) and \emph{crystal/electronic structure} (the
structural motif that gives rise to the desired combination of high Seebeck
coefficient, low electrical resistivity, and low thermal conductivity).
Table~\ref{tab:te_classes} summarises the principal subclasses together with
their general performance attributes.  The discussion that follows treats
chalcogenide-based materials in depth before surveying the remaining subclasses.

% ------------------------------------------------------------
\subsection{Chalcogenide-Based Thermoelectrics}
% ------------------------------------------------------------

chalcogenides constitute the most extensively studied and technologically mature
family of thermoelectric materials.  The term \emph{chalcogenide} refers to
compounds formed between a chalcogen sulphur~(S), selenium~(Se), or
tellurium~(Te) and one or more electropositive elements.  The dominance of
this class in thermoelectric research stems from the intrinsic properties of the
chalcogen-metal bond: the large, polarised anions produce a soft, anharmonic
lattice that scatters heat-carrying phonons efficiently, while the partially
covalent bonding sustains reasonable carrier mobilities.

