\subsubsection{Structural and Chemical Basis}
Chalcogenide thermoelectrics span a wide range of crystal structures, fig.\ref{fig:chalcogenide_structures}  yet they
share the common feature that the heavy chalcogen anion acts as both a
phonon-scattering centre and a controller of the valence band topology.
The most representative structural types are:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Rock-salt derivatives.}  Binary and pseudo-binary tellurides
    with the NaCl-type or distorted NaCl-type structure exhibit narrow band gaps
    compatible with Fermi-level tuning by doping. 

    \item \textbf{Layered and van-der-Waals structures.}  Several selenides and
    tellurides adopt layered structures in which covalently bonded slabs are
    separated by weak interlayer interactions.  This structural anisotropy
    introduces a natural phonon-blocking mechanism perpendicular to the layers
    while maintaining in-plane electrical transport, producing intrinsically
    low lattice thermal conductivity.

    \item \textbf{Complex multi-component chalcogenides.}  Quaternary and higher-order chalcogenides, including copper-based systems of the type $\mathrm{Cu_{2}ZnSnSe_{4}}$ or the LAST family ($\mathrm{AgSbTe}$-derivatives), exploit all-scale hierarchical architectures: point-defect scattering at the atomic scale, nanoprecipitates at the nanoscale, and grain boundaries at the mesoscale.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Silicides}

silicides are compositionally described as intermetallic compounds which are made of silicon and a transition or alkaline-earth metals (Fe, Cr, Mn). They are mainly chemical in terms of classification, in which the silicon sub-lattice provides covalent semiconducting properties but leaves the metallic sites to provide the potential of band-structure engineering through elemental substitution. The main advantage of silicides is due to the terrestrial abundance and non-toxicity of silicon, but their main disadvantage is the relatively high lattice thermal conductivity, which is largely due to the light mass of silicon and strong bonding to that element, limiting the upper values of $zT$ with that of chalcogenides.

\subsubsection{Clathrates}

The crystalline structure is what classifies the clathrates, not the chemical composition. These consist of a host cage structure that is covalently bonded and usually made of group-14 elements (Si, Ge, Sn) and guest atoms (alkali or alkaline-earth metals). The guest atoms will rattle about in oversized cages and this will scatter low-frequency acoustic phonons and significantly undermine thermal conductivity, and the host framework retains the electronic band structure. This rattler is the model realisation of the phonon-glass, electron-crystal (PGEC) concept.
