\subsubsection{Skutterudites}

The skutterudites are also structural classifications. The ideal structure consists of octahedrally coordinated pnictogen (As, Sb, P) rings around the transition metals forming open icosahedral holes that can be filled up (or partially) by heavy rare-earth or alkaline-earth atoms. Such filler atoms are rattled in the clathrates, which are equivalent to the guest species in clathrates. Skutterudites are of particular interest in medium-temperature waste-heat recovery since the compositional freedom in both metal and pnictogen sites allows the independent optimisation of the Seebeck coefficient and carrier concentration.

\subsubsection{Oxides}

Based on the presence of metal oxygen bonds in the chemical definition, and the type of host lattice (perovskite, layered cobaltite, rutile, etc.) in the structural one, thermoelectric oxides can be categorized. Their chief strengths include chemical and thermal stability in air at high temperatures, which make them exceptionally homologous to use in production of high-temperature power without having to use protective casing. They are primarily limited in terms of the wide band gaps and ionic character which tends to inhibit carrier mobility. ref.(k)\,\ref{fig:oxide thermoelctrics}.

