\subsubsection{Half-Heusler Compounds}
Half-Heusler alloys are classified according to crystal structure: alloys of this type take the face-centred cubic MgAgAs-type structure with one of the four tetrahedral sites per unit cell vacated. Such a structure creates 18-electron counts of valence that produce semiconducting behaviour and create strong, stiff lattices  ref.(i,j)\,\ref{fig:HH-FH scahmatic}. As a result, half-Heuslers can incorporate high power factors, due to large carrier effective masses and band degeneracy, with relatively large lattice thermal conductivities. The major approaches to minimization of thermal conductivity and maintaining favourable electronic properties involve nanostructuring and isoelectronic alloying of all three sub-lattices.

A number of other subclasses are currently being investigated, which are either composition-based, or based on the physical mechanism to provide low thermal conductivity some of them are given below:
\paragraph{\textbf{Zintl phases}}  \vspace{-0.5cm}

As compositionally defined polar intermetallics, Zintl phases are those where the electron transfer process of an electropositive cation to a polyanionic structure produces a semiconducting electronic structure. The range of their compositions is enormous and includes hundreds of binary, ternary and quaternary systems ref.(g)\ref{fig:HH-FH scahmatic}.
\paragraph{\textbf{polymers}} \vspace{-0.5cm}

Polymers and organic thermoelectrics are classified based on the conducting-polymer backbone. They are specially adapted to flexible, wearable use at proximate room temperature; however, their $zT$ values are significantly reduced as compared to inorganic counterparts.
\paragraph{\textbf{Zintl phases}}  \vspace{-0.5cm}

 Superionic and liquid-like conductors are defined by a sub-lattice which is dynamically disordered at the operating temperature. The near-liquid phonon mean-free paths resultant propel the lattice thermal conductivity to its theoretical limit.

