\subsection{CuSbSe\textsubscript{2}}
Copper antimony selenide (CuSbSe$_2$) is an emerging earth abundant material of interest for both thermoelectric and photovoltaic applications. The key structural and electronic characteristics of the compound are summarised below, along with the strucutre of Pribramite. 
\begin{figure}[htbp]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.65\linewidth]{book/Images/CH2-images/Strucure of CuSbSe2.png}
    \caption{Schematic of CuSbSe$_2$}
    \label{fig:strucutre of CuSbSe2}
\end{figure}\\
\noindent \textbf{Crystal structure}

CuSbSe$_2$ crystallises in the orthorhombic $Pnma$ space group (No.\,62) with lattice parameters $a = 6.3041$\,\AA, $b = 3.9819$\,\AA, and $c = 15.0102$\,\AA, corresponding to a unit-cell volume of $V = 376.79$\,\AA$^{3}$. The structure is characterised by quasi-two-dimensional bonding and weak van der Waals-like interlayer interactions.

\noindent \textbf{Lattice anharmonicity}

Stereochemically active lone-pair $5s^{2}$ electrons on Sb$^{3+}$ ions induce strong Coulombic repulsion with neighbouring Se ions, producing highly distorted coordination environments and pronounced lattice anharmonicity. This intrinsically suppresses $\kappa_l$ through enhanced phonon scattering.

\noindent \textbf{Electronic structure}

DFT calculations indicate that the valence band maximum (VBM) is dominated by hybridised Cu\,3$d$ and Se\,4$p$ orbitals, yielding relatively flat valence bands, a large DOS effective mass, and consequently a high Seebeck coefficient.

\noindent \textbf{Intrinsic p-type conductivity}

CuSbSe$_2$ exhibits intrinsic p-type conductivity governed by its native defect chemistry. First-principles calculations indicate that copper vacancies ($V_\mathrm{Cu}$) possess low formation energies under Se-rich conditions and act as shallow acceptors, generating holes in the valence band and dominating the observed p-type transport behaviour.

