\subsubsection{Extrinsic Doping}
Aliovalent substitution at the Sb$^{3+}$ site optimises carrier 
concentration whilst intensifying point-defect phonon scattering. Cd 
doping elevated the electronic DOS at the Fermi level, partially 
decoupling the Seebeck coefficient from carrier concentration, yielding 
$\textit{zT} = 0.55$ at 675\,K \cite{M1}. Mn substitution optimised carrier 
mobility, with in-situ Cu$_3$SbSe$_3$ formation reducing $\kappa_l$ by 
$\sim$33\%, achieving $\textit{zT} \sim 0.53$ at 673\,K \cite{C1}. Pb doping 
increased hole concentration via acceptor character, suppressing $\kappa$ 
to $\sim$0.72\,W\,m$^{-1}$\,K$^{-1}$ and giving $zT = 0.27$ at 
623\,K \cite{D1}.

\subsubsection{Intrinsic Defect Engineering}
Sb vacancies in CuSb$_{1-x}$Se$_2$ act as intrinsic acceptors, shifting 
the Fermi level deeper into the valence band and increasing the DOS 
effective mass. This boosted the Seebeck coefficient by $\sim$70\% whilst 
enhancing phonon scattering, culminating in $zT = 0.50$ at 673\,K \cite{H1}.

\subsubsection{Compositing and Secondary Phases}
Off-stoichiometry in CuSbSe$_2$ readily precipitates secondary phases 
such as Cu$_3$SbSe$_4$ and Cu$_3$SbSe$_3$, sometimes Sb$_2$Se$_3$ and Cu$_2$Se. Intentional Cu$_3$SbSe$_4$ nano-inclusions ($\sim$30\,nm) improved carrier injection whilst scattering phonons, raising $zT$ to 0.41 at 623\,K \cite{F1}. A solid-state MA-HP 
route leveraged the inherent multiphase microstructure to scatter phonons 
without critically impairing charge transport, achieving $zT = 0.28$ at 
623\,K \cite{K1}.

