The minimization of the thermophysical properties remains the most common 
approach to the increase of the dimensionless figure of merit, $zT$, in 
the context of thermoelectrics. The specific heat ($C_p$, J\,kg$^{-1}$\,K$^{-1}$) 
is the major thermophysical quantity considered; it is defined as the 
amount of heat needed, at constant pressure, to raise the temperature of 
a substance by one degree Celsius, and the thermal conductivity, which is 
the measure of how much heat a substance conducts per unit area of 
cross-section.

Periodic and Transient heat-flow procedures are broadly considered to be 
experimental approaches to thermal diffusivity determination. Periodic 
or oscillatory thermal treatments, whereby thermal diffusivity is 
determined by examining resultant propagation of temperature waves, phase 
lag, amplitude attenuation.

On the other hand, transient heat-flow methods use a pulse of heat to 
probe the thermal behaviour of the material. Thermal diffusivity is 
determined by examination of how temperature variations change with time. 
These methods have of late become more prominent, due to their high 
accuracy, reduced sample volume requirements, greater reproducibility, 
and their use in a wide range of materials --- thin film, liquids and 
bulk solids.

