The initial and boundary conditions can be used in order to solve this heat conduction equation, more precisely. which  The general solution for the equation can be written for a sample of thickness L at a specific temperature T, time t, assuming no heat loss.defined by Parker et al., ~\cite{1961-parker}
\begin{equation}
    T(x,t)=\frac{1}{L}\int_{0}^{L}f(x)dx+\frac{2}{L}\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}e^{\left(-n^{2}\pi^{2}a\frac{t}{L^{2}}\right)}\cos\frac{n\pi x}{L}\int_{0}^{L}f(x)\cos\frac{n\pi x}{L}dx
    \label{ogparker eq}
\end{equation}
where f(x) represents the temperature distribution from a laser  absorbed by a sample with surface area g, with a pulse of energy Q can be seen as shown in the figure \ref{tikz-lfa}. The primary conditions for the temperature distribution can be shown as:
\[
f(x)=
\begin{cases}
\dfrac{Q}{\rho C g}, & 0 \le x \le g \\[6pt]
0, & g \le x \le L
\end{cases}
\]
From the above condtions being assumed then the \ref{ogparker eq}
can be rewritten as 
\begin{equation}
    T(x,t)=\frac{Q}{\rho CL}\left[1+2\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\cos\frac{n\pi x}{L}\frac{\sin\left(n\pi g/L\right)}{n\pi g/L}e^{\left(\frac{-n^{2}\varepsilon^{2}}{L^{2}}\alpha t\right)}\right]
\end{equation}
as the thickness of the coating (g) can be minute, the equation above can be approximated as ${\left(n\pi g/L\right)}$. Thus the temparature at x= L is, 
\begin{equation}
    T(L,T)=\frac{Q}{\rho CL}\left[1+2\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}{(-1)^{n}}e^{\left(\frac{-n^{2}\pi^{2}}{L^{2}}\alpha t\right)}\right]
\end{equation}
imposing the 2-dimensional condition with the parameters $V(L,t) = T(L,t)/T_{m}$ and $z= \frac{\pi^{2} \alpha t}{L^{2}} $ shall lead to the simplification of the above equation to: 
\begin{equation}
    V=\left[1+2\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}{(-1)^{n}e^{\left(-n^{2}z\right)}}\right]
\end{equation}
where, $T_{M}$ is the maximum temparature at x = L.  The obtaining plot of V vs z can be realised as the infamous Parker curve function \ref{parker-stimuted function}. Which helps us to determine thermal diffusivity of a material, to be: 
\begin{equation}
    \alpha=\frac{1.38L^{2}}{\pi^{2}t_{0.5}}\quad or\quad\alpha=\frac{0.1398L^{2}}{t_{0.5}}
    \label{eq:simple parker}
\end{equation}


