 where t$_{0.5}$ is the time required for the back surface to reach half of the maximum temperature rise. This technique is widely used to determin the thermal conductivity but the Parker halftime method assumes adiabatic boundary condition, i.e no heat loss \ref{eq:simple parker}. However, in realistic scenarion such interactions are inconvertibly existing which can be caused by sources such as specimen holder, and the Protective gas present in the chamber, e.t.c.~\cite{2025-blumm}\\
\noindent However in such conditions Cowan ~\cite{1963-cowen} has shown that the Half-maxima temperature rise time does not correspond to the universal constant z =1.38, but instead depends on heat loss parameters.This introduces systematic errors in thermal diffusivity if uncorrected, Cowan has given correction methods based on theoretical curves or temperature ratios, which can be used to obtain accurate thermal diffusivity as given in the following equation:
 \begin{equation}
R = \frac{\theta(5t_{0.5})}{\theta(t_{0.5})}
\quad \text{or} \quad
R = \frac{\theta(10t_{0.5})}{\theta(t_{0.5})}
\end{equation}
where $\theta$ is the temparature (y-axis) and the $t_{0.5}$ is the detector respose time (x-axis).    

In contemporary practice, most of the evaluation/analysis procedure are based on fitting the complete detector response curve using advanced analytical solutions of transient heat conduction equation, or alternately by numerical fitting the experimental measured responses. Hence the \ref{eq:simple parker} derived originally from Parker ~\cite{1961-parker} which is derived under adiabatic conditions, can be now regarded as obsolete and insufficient for accurate determination of thermal diffusivity.

