\section{Speed of Sound measurement}
Accurate modelling of lattice thermal conductivity in the Debye model requires precise values of acoustic sound velocities in the material. The transverse and longitudinal sound velocities are particularly significant in this regard, due to the direct analogy between the role of the measured sound velocity and the effective mass in the single parabolic band model, in which one measured value is used as an average over a more complex distribution. This analogy, identified by Alex \textit{et al.},\ \cite{91}, enables the sound velocity to be used as an average over all phonon modes in the solid, in the same way that the effective mass is used to characterise charge carrier motion.
For a polycrystalline material with density \textit{d}, shear modulus \textit{G}, and bulk modulus \textit{K}, longitudinal and transverse sound velocities can be calculated using the following equations:

\begin{equation}
    v_{\ long} = \sqrt{\left( \frac{K + \frac{4}{3} G}{d}\right)}
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
    v_{\ trans} = \sqrt{\left( \frac{G}{d}\right)}
\end{equation}
The pulsed-echo ultrasound technique was employed using an Olympus SX 
phased-array flaw detector. This conceptually simple time-of-flight 
measurement is used across various applications for non-destructive 
material analysis. A schematic of this setup can be found here. The setup 
consists of a piezoelectric transducer (a pickup transducer and a drive 
transducer) coupled to the sample on each side, with water as the coupling 
medium to transfer the vibration. A short wave pulse at a frequency of the 
order $10^{7}$\,Hz extremely minute in comparison to the Debye 
frequency of most materials, which is of the order $10^{12}$\,Hz is 
employed to measure phonon modes very near to the centre of the Brillouin 
zone ($q = 0$).\newline 
