\section{Electrical Transport measurements}

The Linseis LSR is used to measure electrical resistivity and the Seebeck coefficient, between room temperature and 600~K. The heating system utilises halogen lamps with the provision of a feedback mechanism to control the required temperature. One should keep in mind that sample oxidation, reaction of the sample with the probes, and sample deposition on the probes are factors that need to be taken into consideration when measuring at high temperatures. The Pribramite based samples are measured under a helium atmosphere. 

The samples were cut into bar-shaped geometries with uniform dimensions before measurement so that the cross-section and length of the sample could yield the correct resistivity. The surfaces of the samples were polished meticulously to provide good mechanical contact with the probes. The ohmic character of the contacts was verified by current voltage ($I$--$V$) characterisation before loading into the instrument, ensuring that the observed resistance reflects the intrinsic bulk resistivity of the sample rather than being confounded by artefacts arising from contact resistance. A standard Constantan sample has also been checked prior to confirm that the probes are functioning correctly. 

\begin{figure}
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.45\linewidth]{book/Images/CH2-images/schematic setup lsr.png}
    \caption{Schematic of Linsies Seebeck Resistivity setup, ref.\cite{lsrwebsite}}
    \label{fig:LSR setup}
\end{figure}

The electrical resistivity is determined by the four-probe method, as shown in Fig.\ref{fig:LSR setup}. A constant current of 20~mA is passed through the sample via the upper and lower platinum probes, and the voltage drop is recorded by the S-type Pt/Rh thermocouples placed on the sides. The resistance is calculated using Ohm's law, and the resistivity is determined from the sample dimensions. All contacts are pressure contacts. This four-probe arrangement removes the contribution of contact resistance from the measurement, making it especially appropriate for low-resistivity thermoelectric samples where contact resistance may otherwise dominate.

To measure the Seebeck coefficient, a heater installed in the lower electrode block maintains a temperature gradient of 20~K across the sample. The Pt/Rh thermocouples measure the temperature difference and the voltage drop at the contacts. The Seebeck coefficient is obtained using the formula $S = -\mathrm{d}V/\mathrm{d}T$, which yields the relative Seebeck coefficient, as the probe contribution is also present. Since a temperature gradient exists across the sample, the sample temperature is taken as the average of the readings recorded by the two thermocouples. Measurements are performed within a temperature tolerance of 10~K, as precise stabilisation at each target temperature is not feasible.
