At each measurement interval, the sample was allowed to dwell for 2~minutes to ensure thermal stability before data acquisition. Three data points were recorded at each temperature interval and subsequently averaged to improve measurement reliability and reduce statistical noise.

To further assess sample stability and account for any effects arising from surface oxidation or structural changes at elevated temperatures, both heating and cooling cycles were performed. Agreement between the heating and cooling curves serves as a diagnostic of sample integrity and confirms the reproducibility of the measured transport properties across the temperature range.


\section{X-Ray Diffraction}
In the material characterization strategy, the diffraction method has become one of the techniques that have been widely used, and has been the center of the scientific inquiry since it was discovered by Roentgen in 1895. X-ray diffraction is also one of the basic wave-optical effects which occur as a result of electromagnetic radiation interplay with matter, which includes such processes as polarization, diffraction, reflections and refraction.


In powder diffraction, a poly-crystalline sample of randomly oriented crystallites is irradiated by monochromatic X-ray. Since the crystallites will fill all orientations, a sub-set will always be able to meet the diffraction condition of a particular set of lattice planes.
\begin{equation}
n\lambda = 2d_{hkl} \sin\theta,
\end{equation}
with n being order of diffraction, $\lambda$ the X-ray wavelength, dhkl being the inter planar spacing of the Miller indices (hkl) and 0 (hkl) being the Bragg angle.

There are two primary mechanisms for generating X-rays. Thermionic emission is used in laboratory-scale equipment to provide the electron beam: a tungsten filament, heated to high temperatures, emits electrons from its surface by thermal emission; a high voltage then accelerates the beam onto a metallic target anode. The most commonly used laboratory target is copper (Cu), which emits characteristic X-radiation with a wavelength of ${1.5406 \ A }$ (Cu K$_\alpha$ radiation). Synchrotron sources are an even better alternative for applications that require higher collimated X-radiation brilliance and tunable wavelength. 
