The intensity of each diffracted peak is determined by the electron density distribution in the unit cell as the X-rays interact with the electron cloud that surrounds the nuclei of atoms. Relative magnitudes of the peaks are controlled by the structure factor which is dependent on the arrangement of the atoms and the distribution of electrons in the unit cell. Therefore, P-XRD (Powder X-Ray Diffraction) allows the identification of crystalline phases, determination of lattice parameters, identification of secondary phases, and measurement of crystallinity.

In addition to phase identification, analysis of broadening of peaks can also be used to obtain additional structural information, including crystallite size and micro strain, by use of powder diffraction. Debye-Scherrer equation gives an approximation of the average crystallite size based on full width at half maximum of diffraction peaks.

\begin{equation}
\tau = \frac{K \lambda}{\beta \cos\theta}
\label{eq:deby-scherrer}
\end{equation}

$\tau$ is the mean size of the ordered (crystalline) domains, which may be smaller than or equal to the grain size;
 $K$ is the dimensionless shape factor, typically close to unity. A commonly used value is approximately $0.9$, although it depends on the actual shape of the crystallites;
 $\lambda$ is the X-ray wavelength;
 $\beta$ is FWHM of the diffraction peak,This quantity is denoted as $\Delta(2\theta)$; \newline  
