\section{UV-Vis-NIR Spectroscopy}
Optical characterisation via Ultraviolet-Visible-Near Infrared (UV-Vis-NIR) 
spectroscopy constitutes a cornerstone technique in the study of electronic 
structure and optical behaviour of semiconducting materials. The underlying 
principle relies on the interaction of electromagnetic radiation, spanning 
the ultraviolet (200--400\,nm), visible (400--800\,nm), and near-infrared 
(780--2000\,nm) spectral ranges, with the material under investigation. 
Upon incidence, photons of sufficient energy may undergo absorption, 
transmission, or reflection, with the relative proportion of each process 
governed directly by the electronic band structure of the material.

The value that can be mainly seen in a UV-Vis-NIR experiment is the absorbance A, which has an association with the transmittance T of the sample by:
\begin{equation}
    A = -\log_{10}(T) = -\log_{10}\!\left(\frac{I}{I_{0}}\right)
\end{equation}
In which, I$_o$ is the intensity of incident radiation and I is the intensity of radiation that penetrates the sample. In the case of thin-film and solid-state samples, the absorbance can also be connected to the absorption coefficient, and the sample thickness by the Beer-Lambert's law:
\begin{equation}
    A = \alpha t \log_{10}(e) = \frac{\alpha t}{2.303}
\end{equation}
The physical mechanism behind optical absorption in semiconductors.
When a photon of energy $h\nu$ greater than E$_g$ hits the material it gets absorbed by the promotion of an electron out of the valence band into the conduction band and leaves behind a hole. Such electron-hole pair (or exciton) is the elementary unit of optical absorption in semiconductors.

In powders and polycrystalline samples, large scattering is due to grain boundaries, surface roughness and porosity, which makes direct transmission measurements inappropriate. Diffuse-reflectance spectroscopy in this case is applied with an integrating sphere, and the KubelkaMunk formalism is utilised in order to recover the absorption coefficient of the sampled diffuse reflectance. The KubelkaMunk remission functional is determined as:
\begin{equation}
    F(R_\infty) = \frac{(1 - R_\infty)^2}{2R_\infty} = \frac{\alpha}{s}
    \label{eq:KMq}
\end{equation}
in which $ R_\infty$ is the absolute diffuse reflectance of an optically thick sample with respect to a non-absorbing standard of reference (Barium sulphate, our case/ in general), alpha is the absorption coefficient, and s is the scattering coefficient.

\subsection*{Why Kubelka-Munk and not the Direct Tauc Approach?}

The use of the Kubelka--Munk methodology instead of direct Tauc plot is an absolute requirement of bulk polycrystalline powders. In the original formulation of the Tauc formalism, which is still used for amorphous semiconductors, the absorption edge is caused by a single interband transition between two or more nearly parabolic bands of a three-dimensional solid, a formalism constructed in terms of plots of $(\alpha h\nu)^n$. These conditions are hardly met in actual polycrystalline materials.\newline 
\begin{figure}
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=1\linewidth]{book/Images/CH2-images/Tauc-1.png}
    \caption{Optical band gap measurement, \cite{Klein2023}}
    \label{fig:Tauc-fig}
\end{figure}
Exponential Urbach tail is often caused by defects and structural order ref, fig-a \ref{fig:Tauc-fig}, which lengthens absorption below the actual band edge. The effect changes the onset and can provide extracted bandgap values that are not related to any unique interband transition \cite{Klein2023}. This is further complicated by the fact that the problem is more acute when there are multiple phases that are coexisting or that the direct and indirect transitions are close together in energy, since the absorption edge is reflecting a superposition of processes, as opposed to a single transition. At a large scale, in heavily defected or doped systems, localized in-gap states can control near edge absorption, making the direct Tauc formalism unreliable.
Hence, Diffuse reflectance spectroscopy is the right choice with such samples. 
\newline 

The Kubelka--Munk remission works, the absolute diffuse reflectance ($R_{\infty}$) gives a number proportional to ($\alpha$), when scattering is roughly wavelength independent. Therefore, the Kubelka--Munk transformation is not a choice, it is the physical processing that will lead to any bandgap analysis for bulk materials.

