The energy spectrum of the photoelectrons emitted is measured using an electron analyser. In \index{XPS} XPS spectra, the energies of peaks appearing at certain energies, which are known as core electron lines, are proportional to the binding energy level of the photoelectrons emitted with respect to the Fermi level:
\begin{equation}
E_{b,i} = h\nu - E_i - \phi
\end{equation}

where $\phi$ is the work function, and $\nu$ is the frequency of the exciting radiation. Along with characteristic peaks, other bands of weaker intensity can be observed adjacent to the core electron lines; this corresponds to the distribution of the electronic states in the material of weaker intensity in the valence band. 
\subsection{Errors and Analysis}
XPS data is quite easy to misinterpret sometimes in a subtle way that affects the final conclusions drawn from the data analysis. Therefore, it is essential to discuss the main limitations or potential areas of concern associated with this technique. First of all, XPS is a surface-sensitive technique as the photoelectrons originate from a depth of 0-10 nanometers of the material. \newline This means that if any adventitious carbon or oxide is present on the surface or if any impurities are picked up from the air, this will show up in the spectrum and mask the signals of interest. Although X-rays penetrate deeper into the material, only the low-energy photoelectrons are able to escape without considerable inelastic scattering.\newline Charging is another major limitation of XPS. It is a big concern for insulators as a charge builds up on the surface during emission, which affects the position of the peaks. \newline Another limitation is associated with the resolution of \index{XPS} XPS. It is quite possible that a natural linewidth of 0.7-0.9 eV is associated with a non-monochromated X-ray source, which is too broad to resolve closely spaced chemical environments. Although a monochromated X-ray source reduces this value to 0.25 eV, this is achieved at the expense of a reduced X-ray intensity.
\subsection{Peak Identification and Spectral Features}
The correct identification of peaks in an XPS spectrum requires careful consideration of several factors, as a number of spectral features may arise which are not directly related to the primary photoelectron transitions of interest. The most commonly encountered of these are as follows:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Doublets:} XPS peaks originating from any orbital with non-zero angular momentum appear as doublets as a consequence of spin--orbit coupling, with the relative intensities of each component governed by $2j+1$. The Sn\,3d doublet, for instance, presents a 3:2 intensity ratio between the Sn\,3d$_{5/2}$ and Sn\,3d$_{3/2}$ components.

\item \textbf{Satellite peaks:} When a non-monochromatic x-ray source is employed, multiple characteristic energies irradiate the sample simultaneously, giving rise to additional peaks shifted to lower binding energies relative to the primary peak. These artefacts are absent when a monochromatic source is used.

\item \textbf{Shake-up peaks / Loss features:} These features arise from an inelastic interaction between the outgoing photoelectron and a valence electron during the photoemission process, resulting in peaks displaced to binding energies a few eV above the principal peak.

\item \textbf{Multiplet splitting:} When unpaired electrons occupy valence levels, the resulting exchange interaction with the core hole can split what would otherwise appear as a single peak. This effect is particularly pronounced in the s-orbital spectra of open-shell transition metal compounds such as Co(\textsc{II}), Ni(\textsc{II}), and Cu(\textsc{II}).
\end{itemize}
