The mechanical characterisation is obtained using the terminal unloading part of the load \& displacement trace as the main source of determining the mechanical characterisation. Since the unloading curves of the materials are non-linear in nature, the data are represented by a power-law equation:
P = $\alpha (h - h_f)^m$
where P is the load applied, h is the cumulative displacement, h$_f$ is the cumulative residual depth and h, and m are the constants of fit. By analytically differentiating this power-law at the maximum load and displacement, the initial unloading contact stiffness, $S = dP/dh$ will be obtained.
Contact depth, h$_c$, that measures the portion of vertical motion that produces contact is determined as
$$h c = h{_{max}} - \varepsilon (P max)/S. $$
and where is a geometrical factor, usually 1.05 where a the Berkovich indenter is used. The calculated contact area, A, is then obtained using the indenter calculated area, A = F(h c ). Thus, the hardness, H, can be defined as the average pressure  that the material can support at the load and calculated as
H = $\frac{P_{max}}{A}$
and the smaller elastic modulus is calculated as a product of initial unloading stiffness and area of contact.\newline
Comming to the fundamental physical equation between the macroscopic measure and the inherent elasticity of the material is: 
$$S = \frac{p^2 E_r}{A},$$
In which $A$ is the area of projection of the elastic contact and $E_r$ is the diminished modulus. 
Comming to understanding how to derive the young's modulus from the Load v/s displacemnet curve, as can be seen from the picture the $dP/dh$ cuvrve indicate the stiffness of the constact, lets us name it "S" this is a codependent propert with of ths smaple and the contsct, this is used to calculate the reduces Young's modulus E$_r$ :
\begin{equation}
