In material analysis, SEM and \index{EDX} EDX are used together, where a synergistic effect is realized. Although SEM can be used to visually visualise the morphology of grain boundaries and their effects on mechanical and thermal properties, EDX can provide complementary compositional information that visualises distributions of elements on grain boundaries. The joint information helps get the hints about the elemental diffusion rates and the formation of various phases within the crystalline lattice.

The technical provisions of SEM EDX are designed to conform to the high requirements of the modern science of materials. Even the tiniest features known to a boundary, which can be seen under magnifications of 50,000×, can be observed with SEM, but along with stoichiometric analyses can be provided at a resolution of about 100 nm with EDX. These modalities provide a overall picture of the structural and chemical properties of a specimen, and together they combine them to create an overall picture necessary in materials studies, and in materials applications. The theoretical validation based on the findings extrapolated on SEM images and EDX data is the foundation and a format to follow in designing materials with the desired properties and functionality. 

