\section{X-Ray Diffraction}
X-ray diffraction patterns of the CuSbSe$_{2-x}$Te$_x$ series have been provided, and reference patterns have been found in the Inorganic Crystal Structure Database ICSD as entry 128918 of CuSbSe$_2$ and 629005 of CuSbTe$_2$. The fact that the experimental and reference peaks were near each other shows that all the desired phases were formed without the appearance of any secondary phases.
\begin{figure}[htbp]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.75\linewidth]{book/Images/4-Analysis images/xrd-all.png}
    \caption{Powder X-ray diffraction of CuSbSe$_{2-x}$Te$_{x}$, (x $\in$ 0, 0.5, 1.0, 1.5 and 2.0)}
    \label{fig:XRD for all samles}
\end{figure}
A first-order increase of tellurium to level $x = 0.5$ causes the diffraction peaks to shift to larger values of $2\theta$ and according to the Bragg law itmeans that the interplanar distance $d$ becomes smaller. With an increase inthe tellurium content up to $x \geq 1.0$ and beyond, there is acounterintuitive decrease in the value of $2\theta$, indicating an expansion of $d$ which can be explained by the increased ionic radius of Te$^{2-}$ compared with Se$^{2-}$.

Moreover, the complexity of the XRD pattern decreases with an increase in the content of tellurium. The abundance of highly resolved peaks typical of orthorhombic CuSbSe$_2$ are significantly fewer in number than in CuSbTe$_2$, which is indicative of an increase in crystal symmetry that is accompanied by increased tellurium concentrations. This decrease in the number of reflections is due to the fact that a number of reflections will be degenerate as the symmetry is increased.
