\section{Raman Spectrosopy}
\begin{figure}[htbp]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=1\linewidth]{book/Images/4-Analysis images/all-pellet and podwer-Raman.png}
    \caption{Raman of CuSbSe$_{2-x}$Te$_{x}$, (x=0, 0.5, 1.0, 1.5 and 2.0) powder (left), and pellet (right)} 
    \label{fig:all-raman-pellet-podwer}
\end{figure}
The Raman spectra of the CuSbSe$_{2-x}$Te$_x$ series were recorded over the
range 100--500\,cm$^{-1}$ and are presented in order of increasing Te content.
The representation of vibrational modes in CuSbSe$_2$ is given as
$$
M = 8A_g + 4A_u + 4B_{1g} + 8B_{1u} + 8B_{2g} + 4B_{2u} + 4B_{3g} + 8B_{3u}
$$
where the Raman-active modes are $A_g$, $B_{1g}$, $B_{2g}$, and $B_{3g}$.
For the parent compound CuSbSe$_2$, the spectrum displays the richest set of vibrational features, consistent with the low-symmetry orthorhombic structure.\\
The dominant peak at 211\,cm$^{-1}$ is assigned to the $A_g$ mode of the
CuSbSe$_2$ phase, which is singly degenerate with symmetry about the inversion centre is absent. Additional features at 190\,cm$^{-1}$ and 254\,cm$^{-1}$ are attributed to secondary phase contributions from either binary Sb$_2$Se$_3$ or ternary Cu$_3$SbSe$_3$, which are difficult to distinguish on the basis of Raman alone given the close overlap of their vibrational signatures. \cite{D1} In particular, the mode at 190\,cm$^{-1}$ is consistent with Cu$_3$SbSe$_3$ as a secondary phase, supporting the XRD analysis. The peaks at 372\,cm$^{-1}$ and 452\,cm$^{-1}$ are also present; notably, the charcteristic Cu-Se vibrations. mode exvpected near 259\,cm$^{-1}$ is observed, indicating that there is a isolated Cu-Se binary phase is present.
The peaks has seemed to have a Blue shift as given stronger Cu-X bonds that are being formed with increasing Te at$\%$, it is also note worthy that the peak broadening is evident, thus this may resulting an idea of short phonon lifetimes. 

