\section{Differential Scanning Calorimetry}
 To evaluate the thermal stability of the samples, we have conducted Differential scanning calorimetry (DSC), from RT to 773K, with a heating/cooling rate of 10$^{\circ}$/min. The CuSbSe$_{2-x}$Te$_x$ series are presented in Figure~\ref{fig:desnity dsc}.  

 \begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \begin{minipage}[t]{0.4\textwidth}
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{book/Images/4-Analysis images/DSC.png}
    \end{minipage}%
    \hfill
    \begin{minipage}[t]{0.53\textwidth}
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{book/Images/4-Analysis images/density png.png}
    \end{minipage}%
    \caption{Thermal stability analysis of CuSbSe$_x$Te$_{2-x}$ (to left); Density of the compacted pellets using Archimedes' method. (to right) }
    \label{fig:desnity dsc}
\end{figure}
\vspace{-0.5cm}

 All compositions show a broadly flat baseline from 300 to 600\,K, indicating thermal stability  across this range. CuSbSe$_2$ exhibits a sharp, intense endothermic dip at approximately 750\,K, which is exaclty to the previously reported values for the system. Upon partial Te substitution, CuSbSe$_{1.5}$Te$_{0.5}$ shows a broader endothermic  feature at $\sim$720\,K, suggestive of a possible in-congruent melting. 

CuSbSeTe retains a comparably sharp endothermic dip, now shifted to $\sim$700\,K, consistent with  progressive melting point depression as Te is incorporated into the lattice. For  CuSbSe$_{0.5}$Te$_{1.5}$, the feature broadens further and diminishes in intensity at $\sim$710\,K,  indicative of a wider melting range arising from increased compositional disorder or a miscibility  gap in this intermediate composition. 

CuSbTe$_2$ is largely stable across the measured range,  with only a small dip near 720\,K that is likely attributable to a minor impurity phase rather than  a bulk transition; the parent compound may melt beyond the scan window, or the transition is  sufficiently sluggish to be unresolved. The small feature is consistent with a secondary Cu-Te  binary impurity in the 700 to 750\,K region.

In short, the transition temperature decreases progressively from Se-rich to intermediate  compositions, and the peak sharpness vanishes with increasing Te content.

