\section{Rietveld refinement}
Rietveld refinement of the powdered samples were analysed using Crystal Diffract application. 
\subsection{Rietveld refinement of CuSbSe\textsubscript{2}}
Rietveld refinement of the powder XRD pattern confirms that the synthesised CuSbSe$_2$ crystallises in the orthorhombic Pribramite structure with space group $Pnma$. The refined lattice parameters $a = 6.3067(2)$~\AA, $b = 3.9849(1)$~\AA, $c = 15.0146(4)$~\AA, and unit cell volume $V = 377.34(2)$~\AA$^3$ are in good agreement with previously reported values for this compound, confirming phase-pure synthesis of the target structure. 
\begin{figure}
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\linewidth]{CuSbSe_2(refined) .png}
    \caption{Rietveld refinement of CuSbSe$_2$ }
    \label{fig:Refinement for CuSbSe2}
\end{figure}
The data is consistent with the layered character of CuSbSe$_2$, where CuSe$_4$ tetrahedra and SbSe$_5$ square pyramids are stacked along $[001]$ with weakly bound interlayer van der Waals gaps separating the structural units along this direction.

A minor secondary phase of Sb$_2$Se$_3$ (space group $Pnma$, ICSD~194837) was identified at 6.32~wt\%, with refined lattice parameters $a = 11.8091(5)$~\AA, $b = 3.9860(2)$~\AA, $c = 11.6186(4)$~\AA, consistent with literature values. Its presence is commonly observed in CuSbSe$_2$ synthesis. The near coincidence of the $b$-parameter of Sb$_2$Se$_3$ ($3.9860$~\AA) with that of CuSbSe$_2$ ($3.9849$~\AA) reflects the shared Sb-Se chain periodicity in both orthorhombic structures. 

The weighted profile residual $R_{wp} = 9.29\%$ against $R_{exp} = 0.81\%$ indicates scope for further improvement of the structural model, primarily through refinement of atomic displacement parameters, which were not included in the present refinement cycle.

The low $R_{exp} = 0.81\%$ and consequently the inflated $\chi^2$ is a direct consequence of the high photon statistics in the measurement rather than any property of the structural model. $R_{exp}$ is defined as:
%
\begin{equation}
    R_{exp} = \sqrt{\frac{N - P}{\sum w_i y_i^2}}
\end{equation}
%
where $N$ is the number of data points, $P$ the number of refined parameters, and $w_i y_i^2$ the weighted intensity at each point. 

\subsection{Rietveld refinement of CuSbTe\textsubscript{2}}

Rietveld refinement of the powder XRD pattern of the nominally CuSbTe$_2$ 
sample confirms the absence of the target chalcostibite ternary phase, 
identifying instead two co-existing binary phases: weissite (Cu$_{1.8}$Te) 
and tellurantimony (Sb$_2$Te$_3$), consistent with the ICSD structural 
models employed. The synthesis has therefore resulted in phase separation 
into these two binary compounds rather than formation of the ternary 
chalcostibite structure.
\begin{figure}
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\linewidth]{CuSbTe2-Refined.png}
    \caption{Rietveld refinement of CuSbTe$_2$ }
    \label{fig:Refinemetn for CuSbTe2}
\end{figure}
The refined phase weight fractions are 44.18\% and 55.82\% for 
Cu$_{1.8}$Te and Sb$_2$Te$_3$ respectively, with corresponding phase 
volume fractions of 40.67\% and 59.33\%. The divergence between weight 
and volume fractions is physically self-consistent and reflects the 
significant density difference between the two phases, Cu$_{1.8}$Te 
(weissite) being considerably denser than Sb$_2$Te$_3$.

The weissite phase refines in its hexagonal structure with 
$a = b = 8.258(3)$~\AA\ and $c = 21.508(8)$~\AA, giving a unit cell 
volume of $V = 1270.2(8)$~\AA$^3$. The structure is characterised by 
24 distinct partially occupied Cu sites, reflecting the well known 
disordered nature of Cu$_{2-x}$Te, where copper atoms are distributed 
over multiple partially occupied sites within the tellurium framework. 
The large standard uncertainties on the Cu fractional coordinates are 
a direct consequence of this disorder: with so many partially occupied, 
closely spaced Cu sites, the diffraction data cannot uniquely resolve 
individual copper positions and strong inter-site correlations are 
inevitable.

The Sb$_2$Te$_3$ phase refines in the rhombohedral structure with 
$a = b = 4.222(2)$~\AA\ and $c = 30.63(1)$~\AA, giving 
$V = 472.8(3)$~\AA$^3$, in good agreement with reported literature 
values. The refined fractional coordinates for Sb1 ($z = 0.39880(5)$) 
and Te1 ($z = 0.78720(3)$) are well-determined with small standard 
uncertainties, consistent with the ordered nature of this phase. The 
displacement parameters are physically reasonable: 
$U_{iso}(\mathrm{Sb1}) = 0.018(3)$~\AA$^2$, 
$U_{iso}(\mathrm{Te1}) = 0.0063(31)$~\AA$^2$, and 
$U_{iso}(\mathrm{Te2}) = 0.010(3)$~\AA$^2$.

\indent The phase compositions identified by Rietveld \index{Refinement} Refinement are 
independently corroborated by SEM-EDS analysis, which resolves two 
chemically distinct microstructural regions. The dark copper-rich areas 
yield a composition of Cu$_{61.09 \pm 1.5}$Sb$_{1.70 \pm 0.07}$%
Te$_{37.25 \pm 1.51}$~at.\%, consistent with off-stoichiometric 
Cu$_{1.8}$Te carrying a trace Sb impurity of $\sim$1.70~at.\%. The 
measured Cu\,:\,Te ratio of $\approx 1.64$ is sub-stoichiometric 
relative to ideal Cu$_2$Te (Cu\,:\,Te $= 2.0$), confirming the 
weissite identity of this phase, where copper vacancies are 
thermodynamically well-established in the Cu$_{2-x}$Te family. The 
white antimony-rich areas yield Cu$_{3.15 \pm 0.62}$Sb$_{38.86 \pm 
0.24}$Te$_{58.00 \pm 0.38}$~at.\%, in close agreement with ideal 
Sb$_2$Te$_3$ stoichiometry (Sb$_{40}$Te$_{60}$), with $\sim$3~at.\% 
Cu accommodated on interstitial sites within the van der Waals gaps of 
the rhombohedral structure.
\begin{figure}
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.9\linewidth]{book/Images/4-Analysis images/Te2-Hp images/Te2-point scan.png}
    \caption{Phase analysis of CuSbTe\textsubscript{2}}
    \label{fig:Te2-SEM}
\end{figure}
The weighted profile residual $R_{wp} = 27.76\%$ against 
$R_{exp} = 1.02\%$ gives $\chi^2 = 745.89$, which is severely elevated. 
This is physically interpretable rather than a Refinement artefact, and 
arises from three concurrent sources. First, the weissite structure 
with its 24 partially occupied Cu sites produces poorly constrained 
calculated intensities that cannot accurately reproduce the observed 
peak intensities. Second, the $\sim$1.70~at.\% Sb dissolved in the 
Cu$_{1.8}$Te phase and the $\sim$3~at.\% Cu incorporated into the 
Sb$_2$Te$_3$ van der Waals gaps as confirmed by EDS are not 
accounted for in the ideal binary ICSD models, introducing systematic 
errors in both peak positions and intensities throughout the full 
$2\theta$ range. Third, the instrument profile parameters show signs 
of instability: $GW$ has refined to an effectively zero value 
($1.3 \times 10^{-11}$) and the asymmetry parameter uncertainty is 
unphysically large, indicating that the profile model has not converged, 
likely due to the dominance of residuals from the structurally 
disordered weissite phase. The mutual impurity contamination observed 
in both phases by EDS therefore directly explains the residual misfit 
between the ideal structural models and the observed diffraction 
pattern, confirming that the elevated $\chi^2$ is a physically 
meaningful indicator of off-stoichiometric phase separation rather 
than a refinement procedure artefact.

