\section{Thermoelectric measurements}
\index{Seebeck} Seebeck coefficient and electrical resistivity measurements were taken at varying 
temperatures ranging from 300~K to 630~K in an attempt to characterise the 
thermoelectric properties of the synthesised samples using the Linseis Seebeck 
Resistivity (LSR) set up. The obtained data can be found in 
Fig.~\ref{fig:Seebeckmeasurement}. Heating and cooling curves were also recorded 
to ensure that the compounds were thermally stable. CuSbSe$_{1.5}$Te$_{0.5}$, 
CuSbSeTe, CuSbSe$_{0.5}$Te$_{1.5}$, and CuSbTe$_2$ were measured.
\begin{figure}
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=1\linewidth]{book/Images/4-Analysis images/Seebeck.png}
    \caption{Temperature dependent conductivity (a); Seebeck (b) and (c) Power factor for heating and cooling cycles of CuSbSe$_1.5$Te$_{0.5}$, CuSbSeTe and CuSbTe$_2$}
    \label{fig:Seebeckmeasurement}
\end{figure}
The pristine CuSbSe$_2$ compound has very high resistivity that is beyond the 
measurement capability of the instrument and could not be directly measured. The 
electrical conductivity of the next composition, CuSbSe$_{1.5}$Te$_{0.5}$, is 
approximately 3~S/cm. With further addition of tellurium up to 50\% (CuSbSeTe), 
the conductivity rises sharply to an average value of $\sim$700~S/cm an 
increase of nearly three orders of magnitude. The end member composition 
CuSbTe$_2$ has a room temperature conductivity of approximately 6000~S/cm, which 
is exceptionally high and is attributed to the presence of the highly metallic 
Cu$_{1.8}$Te secondary phase in the system.

The Seebeck coefficient follows the opposite trend. CuSbTe$_2$ exhibits a low 
Seebeck coefficient, which is typical of a metallic material, whereas the 
selenium-rich compositions show large Seebeck coefficients of $\sim$600~$\mu$V/K. 
Nevertheless, the high Seebeck value in the Se-rich regime is accompanied by a 
prohibitively high resistivity, rendering it inconsistent with viable thermoelectric performance.

