\subsection{CuSbSeTe}
The CuSbSeTe sample was probed in two distinct regions, A$_1$ and A$_2$, to 
investigate the mechanical heterogeneity of the multiphase microstructure. At the 
same maximum load of $P_{max} \approx 1500~\mu$N, region A$_1$ exhibits a maximum 
penetration depth of $h_{max} \approx 130$~nm, whereas region A$_2$ penetrates to 
$h_{max} \approx 230$~nm in the fig.\ref{fig:SeTe-nanoindetation} nearly twice as deep. This stark difference in indentation depth at identical load unambiguously indicates a significant difference in hardness between regions A$_1$ and A$_2$, consistent with the multiphase and microstructurally heterogeneous nature of CuSbSeTe as confirmed by XRD and EDS analysis. \newline 
\begin{figure}[htbp]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.75\linewidth]{book/Images/4-Analysis images/Nanoindentation/SeTe-nanoindent.png}
    \caption{Load v/s Displacement Curve of CuSbSeTe along with Cyclic indentation (100 Cycles)}
    \label{fig:SeTe-nanoindetation}
\end{figure}
Both curves exhibit a pop-in event, manifesting as a discontinuity in the loading 
segment. In A$_1$, this occurs at $\sim$900~$\mu$N, whereas in A$_2$ it occurs at 
the considerably lower load of $\sim$400~$\mu$N, indicating an earlier onset of 
plasticity and dislocation nucleation in the softer region.

This distinction is further corroborated by the cyclic indentation curves. The 
loops in A$_1$ are tighter and more closely stacked, indicating lower plastic 
energy dissipation per cycle and a more elastically dominant response. In contrast, 
the loops in A$_2$ are broader and more widely separated, reflecting greater $W_p$ 
per cycle and a more plastically deformable character, indicating that A$_2$ 
corresponds to a mechanically softer and more compliant region within the 
microstructure.

