\chapter{Conclusion and Future outlook}

\section{Conclusion}
The main idea behind this thesis was to investigate the possibility of a compositional engineering approach based on systematic chalcogen substitution (i.e. replacing Se with Te) to suppress lattice \index{thermal conductivity} thermal conductivity and improve electrical transport, thus pushing the thermoelectric figure of merit \textit{zT} higher than what the pristined CuSbSe$_2$ compound would do in its reported form.

\vspace{0.5em}

The answer that emerges from the totality of the experimental evidence is: partially yes, with significant structural reservations that delimit the scope of this strategy.

\vspace{0.5em}

Using the structural starting point, \textbf{Rietveld refinement} fig.\ref{fig:Refinement for CuSbSe2} \& fig.\ref{fig:Refinemetn for CuSbTe2} proved the crystallisation of parent compound CuSbSe$_2$ in an orthorhombic \textit{Pnma} Pribramite structure with a small Sb$_2$Se$_3$ secondary phase (6.32 wt\%) thermodynamically hard to remove, and in agreement with narrow phase stability window reported in the literature. The synthesis route is justified by the refined lattice parameters, which are well consistent with the reference values. The XRD data shows a non-monotonic change in the d-spacing as the concentration of tellurium is added: a contraction at the beginning at $x = 0.5$ and follows the trend.

\vspace{0.5em}

The parallel decrease in the number of resolved reflections with increasing Te content is evidence of an increase in the series of symmetries, with a direct implication on the phonon landscape and subsequent thermal transport. fig.\ref{fig:XRD for all samles} \& \ref{fig:Thermophyiscal measurement}

\vspace{0.5em}

The structural argument runs into a Te rich wall at the end of the series. Rietveld refinement of nominally CuSbTe$_2$ sample showed not a target ternary phase but a binary phase (eutectic mixture) of Cu$_{1.8}$Te and Sb$_2$Te$_3$,  see fig.\ref{fig:Te2-SEM} which was also independent of SEM/EDS compositional mapping. It is not an artefact of synthesis it is a rather can be viewd as an thermodynamic fact about the stability of such a system: the CuSbTe$_2$ ternary phase is not formed under the conditions used, and the attempt by Thermo-Calc to model the phase diagram of this system using the semiconducting materials database is unable to find a stable solution. This discovery however is an inevitable way to rewrite the account of the series: what one can understand about the system at high Te content, that leads a eutectic phase, and some exiting TE properties. 

\vspace{0.5em}
%
%This is a structural understanding that is critical in understanding the transport data in a proper manner. The fact that the electrical conductivity increases dramatically as x decreases, namely, it is between 0.5 and 0.1 that this conductivity increases by a factor of 6000 times in the case of the CuSbTe$_2$ composite, is not indicative of an effective band engineering in the Pribramite not only scheme. 
%
%\vspace{0.5em}

Once can say that, It rather is a result of the highly metallic Cu$_{1.8}$Te phase, which dominates electrical conductivity, see fig.(a)\ref{fig:Seebeckmeasurement} and at the same time it collapses the Seebeck coefficient to values typical of a metal. The high Seebeck coefficient with Selenium rich compositions (e.g. 600 mV/K) fig.(b)\ref{fig:Seebeckmeasurement} is physically significant and in line with the large DOS effective mass of the flat valence bands of CuSbSe$_2$, but makes the material thermoelectrically infeasible with the prohibitively large electrical resistivity of almost intrinsic material. This is the main conflict of the CuSbSe$_2$ and which the literature has long since recognised and which this work alone proves: the intrinsic carrier density is too small to allow efficient thermoelectric operation without extrinsic optimisation in Pribramite.

\vspace{0.5em}

 \textbf{DSC} has validated that these intermediate compositions are thermodynamically stable within the thermoelectrically accessible temperature range to a temperature of at least 700 K, fig.\ref{fig:desnity dsc} and with a steady melting point reduction and broadening of the maximum to a measure of correspondingly increasing configurational disorganization. The optical bandgap is monotonically decreasing with decreasing energy, with 1.03 eV in CuSbSe$_2$ and 0.60 eV in CuSbTe$_2$, fig.\ref{fig:UVDRS-all} as the topology of the valence bands is reconfigured by progressive lowering of the conduction band minimum by increasing numbers of TE 5p orbitals, which are high-energy orbitals compared to Se 4p orbitals. This contraction of the bandgap is the optical signature of the electronic structure change that causes the conductivity enhancement through the series.

\vspace{0.5em}

\textbf{XPS analysis} showed that the expected oxidation states at the compositional range, i.e. Cu$^+$, Sb$^{3+}$, S$^{2-}$ and Te$^{2-}$, are observed, but with a broader linewidth in the Te rich sample due to the increased structure disorder of the binary phase mixture and not the change of oxidation state.fig.\ref{fig:Te2-XPS} \& fig.\ref{fig:XPs for CuSBSe2} The contribution of surface oxides, in the Sb 3d region although in fact a measurement artefact of the surface sensitivity of \index{XPS} XPS, a convenient reminder of the propensity of antimony to oxidise, is an inconvenient fact when it comes to interpreting binding energies in this system.

\vspace{0.5em}

\textbf{The Nanoindentation} mechanical characterisation provides an added dimension that is hardly reported in thermoelectric research on the material family. CuSbSe$_2$ is the hardest member in the series with a lower modulus of approximately 62 GPa and systematic softening follows the Te replacement to the CuSbTe$_2$ composite where penetration depths would increase nearly twice with the same load, ref.\ref{fig:all-nanoindetation data}. This is physically unbiased with the weakening of metal-chalcogen bond strength with the additional electronegative Te substituting Se, and is useful in practice where the design aspect of thermomechanical stability in cycling is a consideration. This is further supported by the region resolved indentation of CuSbSeTe and CuSbTe$_2$, where soft Cu-rich areas and hard Sb-chalcogenide areas can be differentiated by their patterns of P v/s h curves.

\vspace{0.5em}

The combination of the measured value of dimensionless figure of merit \textit{zT} as high as 0.3 at 630 K in the current series compared to 0.1 with pristine CuSbSe$_2$, ref.\cite{D1} is an actual enhancement that can be attributed to the combined action of point defect scattering to suppress \index{thermal conductivity} thermal conductivity in the intermediate compositions, and to a positive change in electrical conductivity. This is accomplished even in the presence of secondary phases, Is an interesting topic to explore.

\section{Future work}
Further kinetically stabilised experiments, such as prolonged annealing, to determine the true equilibrium phase limits using thermodynamic analysis to map the compositional boundary at which the system becomes destabilised into binary phase separation would be of interest, as would off-stoichiometric synthesis throughout the series to determine the role of inherent defects and compositional deviation in determining the structural and transport behaviour of the system. First-principles phase diagram calculations would further complement such efforts by providing theoretical bounds on the miscibility range prior to experimental synthesis.

\vspace{0.5em}
A detailed study on phase stability analysis of CuSbTe$_2$ using CALPHAD is also being currently being explored.

